		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.mathemafrica.org/?p=13659</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>I have seen some people try to blindly use the formulae for volumes of revolution by cylindrical cross-sections and by cylindrical shells, and I thought that I would write a guide as to how I would recommend tackling such problems, as generally just using the formulae will lead you down blind alleys.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve created an example, with an animation, which I hope will help to master this technique.</p>
<p>So, here is a relatively fool-proof strategy:</p>
<ol>
<li>Draw the region which you are going to have to rotate around some axis. This will generally be a matter of:
<ul>
<li>Drawing the curves that you have been given</li>
<li>Finding where they intersect</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Draw the line about which you are supposed to rotate the region</li>
<li>Draw the reflection of the region about the line of rotation: This gives you a slice through the volume that will be formed</li>
<li>Now you have to decide which method to use:
<ul>
<li>Take a slice through the volume perpendicular to the axis of rotation.</li></ul></li></ol>&#8230;]]></description>
